These two found in close proximity in dry/hard condition on Rum River floodplain hardwood debris. Very dense and firm. Photographed dry, so sheen on underside presumably dried mucous. Though somewhat eroded/eaten, apparently gilled. Largest cap diameter about 2 cm.
Maybe Lentinellus?
Also wondering about the presumed Ascomycete growing on the cap of one. Too small for me to measure with any accuracy (fractions of a millimeter).
This is all a long shot. It’s been too dry around here for good prospecting so scraping by.
